crops.description: A fine-flavored South African papaya, pol- linized by a plant from the Sandwich Is- lands.

crops.presented_by: Institute of Paint and Varnish Research, Washing- ton, D. C., through the Bureau of Chem- istry and Soils
crops.description: A large tropical tree of the Brazilian for- ests, with rigid leathery oblong leaves 3 to 5 inches long and shining green above. The greenish, ovoid-cylindrical fruits, about 2 inches long, yield an oil known as Oiticica oil, that is used in the paint and varnish industry.

crops.presented_by: Arthur W. Burrows, American consular agent, Coquimbo
crops.description: A small papaya 312 by 412 inches, with very thin flesh which is highly acid and is used only in making preserves and sirups. The fruit is yellow when ripe with a spicy aromatic flavor and fragrance, but is never eaten fresh.

crops.presented_by: J. I. Case Co., through Reginald S. Castleman, American consul. Porto Alegre
crops.description: A new type of rice developed near Rio Pardo, State of Rio Grande do Sul, which develops abnormally large ears and is a heavy yielder.
Rust-immune wheat developed in Rio Grande do Sul.

The'sausage tree' of eastern tropical Africa becomes 30 to 50 feet high, with rough ternate leaves made up of seven to nine elliptic-oblong leaflets; the large claret-colored flowers are in long spikes, and the blunt sausagelike fruits are 12 to 18 inches long.
